         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">5/6/94. ¶  ¶ As you may wish, dear Dr Dyer, to distribute seeds (fruits) of the best Austral. salt-bushes for sheep-pastures, I have sent a considerably quantity of those of A. halimoides and A. vesic...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">94.06.05a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Thiselton-Dyer</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1891-6. f. 60.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Date stamped</seg>: Royal Gardens Kew 12. JUL. 94., <seg style="font-style: italic; ">annotated in black ink by W. Watson</seg> 353/1894 (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">i.e.</seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">register number in Kew </seg>Inwards Book <seg style="font-style: italic; ">of specimens received</seg>), <seg style="font-style: italic; ">and</seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">in red ink by ?W. Hemsley</seg>: Ackd. 13.7.94 (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">letter not found</seg>). <seg style="font-style: italic; ">There is a </seg>√ <seg style="font-style: italic; ">in red pencil at the top of the page.</seg>
                     <seg style="color: #0000ff; font-weight: bold; "> </seg>
                  </p>
               </note>5/6/94.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As you may wish, dear Dr Dyer, to distribute seeds (fruits) of the best Austral. salt-bushes for sheep-pastures, I have sent a considerably quantity of those of A. halimoides and A. vesicarium,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">A. halimoides <seg style="font-style: italic; ">and</seg> A. vesicarium <seg style="font-style: italic; ">are underlined in red pencil.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> [freshly]<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">A word has been overwritten.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> collected in Central Australia; but I have at present no fruits of A nummularium.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In DC's Flore francaise the most northern locality given for A. Halimus, is the entrance of the Loire (47° N.),<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Lamark &amp; A. P. Candolle (1815), vol. 3, p. 384: 'environs de Guerrande près Nantes’. The 1815 reissue is the edition held in the library at MEL.</p>
               </note> and as the constitution of that shrubby species of Atriplex is likely similar to that of the Australian frutescent species, this would indicate an equal degree of Hardiness; nor could there be any great difference between the climate of Loire coast and that of the South of France. Perhaps you have correspondents also in the Channel-Islands, who would try (thus near to you)<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>thus … to you interlined; <seg style="font-style: italic; ">parentheses added editorially for ease of reading</seg>.</p>
               </note> the Australian Atriplices there for culture. The flocks prefer the Australian inlands saltbushes far to those of the coast, because the latter are <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">too saline</hi>
               </seg>.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
